es the idea that the human self is fundamentally constituted in terms of its relations to others. For relational theorists, the self not only lives in relationship with and to others, but also owes its very existence to such relationships. In this groundbreaking collection, leading relational theorists explore core moral and metaphysical concepts, while health law and policy scholars respond by analyzing how such considerations might apply to more practical areas of concern. Innovative and self-reflexive, Being Relational brings a powerful theoretical framework to health law and policy studies. In so doing, it makes a bold contribution to scholarship and will appeal to a broad range of thinkers, especially those with an interest in social justice, and who seek to understand the complex ways in which power is created and sustained relationally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Health.2bisacsh1 aBaylis, Françoise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeckha, Maneesha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDownie, Jocelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDownie, Jocelyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKoggel, Christine M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLlewellyn, Jennifer J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLlewellyn, Jennifer J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMacIntosh, Constance, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLeod, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNedelsky, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re